# BookNookCorner 📚

A hybrid book recommender system combining **content-based filtering** and
**collaborative filtering** on the Book-Crossing dataset. Built as part of a
university research project on Data Analysis and Data Mining.

## Project Purpose

Reading platforms and libraries hold rich but underused signals — ratings, reading
history, favorite authors and genres — that can be turned into personalized book
suggestions. BookFusion explores whether combining two classic recommendation
strategies produces better suggestions than either strategy alone:

- **Content-based filtering** recommends books similar to ones a user already liked,
  based on title, author, and publisher text features.
- **Collaborative filtering** recommends books liked by *other users with similar
  taste*, learned from the user–item rating matrix.
- **Hybrid model**: a weighted blend of both (`alpha` controls the mix), aiming to
  reduce each method's individual weaknesses — content-based filtering's tendency
  to recommend only near-identical items, and collaborative filtering's cold-start
  problem for users/books with few ratings.

**Target users**: avid readers, students, and library patrons looking for
personalized reading suggestions.

**Output**: a ranked top-10 list of book recommendations per user.

## Dataset Used

[Book-Crossing Dataset](http://www2.informatik.uni-freiburg.de/~cziegler/BX/) — real-world
book ratings collected from the Book-Crossing community.

- ~271K books, ~279K users, ~1.15M ratings (raw)
- After cleaning (removing implicit ratings, missing metadata, and sparse
  users/books with fewer than 5 ratings): **11.5K books, 10.8K users, 119K explicit ratings**

See [`data/README.md`](data/README.md) for full details and download instructions.

## Algorithms Used

| Component | Method |
|---|---|
| Content-based filtering | TF-IDF vectorization (title + author + publisher) + cosine similarity |
| Collaborative filtering | Matrix factorization via Truncated SVD (mean-centered ratings, 30 latent factors) |
| Hybrid merge | Min-max normalized weighted sum: `hybrid = alpha * content + (1 - alpha) * collaborative` |
| Evaluation | RMSE (rating prediction) + Precision@10 / Recall@10 (ranking quality), 80/20 train-test split |

## Project Structure

```
BookNookCorner/
│
├── data/
│   └── README.md              # dataset info (raw CSVs not included, see below)
│
├── src/
│   ├── 01_load_explore.py     # load raw CSVs, inspect shapes/missing values/rating distribution
│   ├── 02_clean.py            # clean & filter books, users, ratings; save *_clean.csv
│   ├── 03_recommender.py      # build content-based, collaborative, and hybrid engine
│   └── 04_evaluate.py         # train/test split, RMSE, Precision@K, Recall@K
│
├── results/
│   ├── evaluation_results.png       # RMSE + Precision/Recall across hybrid weights (alpha)
│   └── recommendation_examples.png  # sample top-10 recommendations for a real user
│
├── README.md
└── requirements.txt
```

## How to Run

1. Clone the repo and install dependencies:
   ```bash
   git clone https://github.com/SenaDok/BookNookCorner.git
   cd BookNookCorner
   pip install -r requirements.txt
   ```

2. Download the Book-Crossing CSVs (see `data/README.md`) and place them in `data/`:
   - `BX_Books.csv`, `BX-Users.csv`, `BX-Book-Ratings.csv`

3. Run the pipeline in order:
   ```bash
   python src/01_load_explore.py   # explore raw data
   python src/02_clean.py          # produces data/*_clean.csv
   python src/03_recommender.py    # generates sample recommendations
   python src/04_evaluate.py       # prints RMSE, Precision@10, Recall@10
   ```

## Results

**Rating prediction (collaborative component):** RMSE = **1.78** (scale 1–10)

**Ranking quality across hybrid weights (alpha = content-based weight):**

| alpha | Precision@10 | Recall@10 |
|---|---|---|
| 0.00 (pure collaborative) | 0.007 | 0.016 |
| 0.25 | 0.017 | 0.055 |
| **0.50 (balanced hybrid)** | **0.020** | **0.068** |
| 0.75 | 0.021 | 0.068 |
| 1.00 (pure content-based) | 0.019 | 0.065 |

The hybrid blend (alpha ≈ 0.5–0.75) outperforms both pure strategies on both metrics,
supporting the case for combining content-based and collaborative signals. Absolute
scores are modest, which reflects the extreme sparsity of the Book-Crossing dataset
(99.9%) — a known and documented challenge in the recommender systems literature,
not a defect of the model.

![Evaluation results](results/evaluation_results.png)
![Sample recommendations](results/recommendation_examples.png)

## Limitations

- Book-Crossing has no genre field; content-based similarity relies on title, author,
  and publisher text only.
- High sparsity (99.9%) limits ranking metrics; collaborative filtering suffers from
  cold-start for users/books with very few ratings.

